The Project: I built this because streaming high-bitrate torrents on a Raspberry Pi often hits hardware bottlenecks. Tiramisu is a unified virtual file system (VFS) that acts as an intelligent proxy, turning remote torrent streams into "local" files for Plex with zero-network metadata latency.
The Impact: I achieved sub-second start times by implementing a "Native Bridge" for in-memory communication and a custom 32-shard inode mapping system using xxHash for zero-allocation performance. The result is a rock-solid, production-ready binary that’s 60% smaller than legacy builds and immune to the scan-deadlocks common on low-RAM devices.

The Project: I created this to bridge the gap between streaming habits and local library management. It’s a self-maintaining engine that watches what you listen to on Last.fm and automatically discovers, filters, and queues new artists into your media managers.

The Impact: Instead of just pulling every recommendation, I built a modular service layer that uses the MusicBrainz API to intelligently filter out low-quality releases (live bootlegs or compilations), ensuring only studio albums hit the library. It includes a robust retry-logic system with exponential backoff to handle API rate limits gracefully, making the discovery process entirely "set and forget."




